<!-- tpl: single-post.php -->
<main class="main" id="content">

	<!-- tpl: template/content.php -->

<article class="post post--regular" id=post-59146>

		<header class="post-header">
					<div class="post-header__text">
			<h5 class="post-header__text__section section"><a href='/creators-communities/'>Creators &amp; Communities</a></h5>
			<h1 class="post-header__text__title" id="headline">Instagram account hacked? “Ethical hackers” will get it back</h1>
			<h3 class="post-header__text__dek">Meta’s account recovery process is so complicated that people are paying experts to do it for them.</h3>
					</div>	<figure class="post-header__image loaded  image image--landscape" >
		<div class="image__container ">
		<div class="image__wrapper " >
		
		<img
			
			src="https://149346090.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/ROW-Brazil-flattened-768x432.jpg"
			srcset="https://149346090.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/ROW-Brazil-flattened-2800x1575.jpg 2800w, https://149346090.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/ROW-Brazil-flattened-1600x900.jpg 1600w, https://149346090.v2.pressablecdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/07/ROW-Brazil-flattened-768x432.jpg 768w, " 
			sizes="(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px"
			alt="An illustration of a hacker in front of a screen with a halo around his head, against a black and green grainy background."
			
		/>
		
		</div>
		</div>
				<figcaption class="figcaption" itemprop="caption description">
		
		<span class='figcaption__credit' itemprop='copyrightHolder'><a href='http://danielzender.com' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>Daniel Zender for Rest of World</a></span>
		</figcaption>
	</figure>		</header>

					<div class="post-image-credit" aria-hidden="false">
						<figcaption class="figcaption" itemprop="caption description">
		
		<span class='figcaption__credit' itemprop='copyrightHolder'><a href='http://danielzender.com' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer'>Daniel Zender for Rest of World</a></span>
		</figcaption>			</div>
		
				<div class="post-subheader">
			
	<div class="post-subheader__byline">By <a href="https://restofworld.org/author/daniela-dib/" title="Posts by Daniela Dib" class="author url fn" rel="author">Daniela Dib</a> and <a href="https://restofworld.org/author/marilia-marasciulo/" title="Posts by Marília Marasciulo" class="author url fn" rel="author">Marília Marasciulo</a></div>
	
	<div class="post-subheader__meta meta">
		<div class="post-subheader__meta-date"> <time datetime="2023-08-21">21 August 2023</time></div>
	</div>

	<div class="post-header__text__summary" aria-role="region" aria-label="summary"><ul><li><span>Authorities in Brazil have warned of a spike in hacked Instagram accounts in the past year.</span></li><li><span>Frustrated by Meta’s slow response, victims are paying individuals who call themselves “hackers éticos” (ethical hackers) to recover their accounts.</span></li><li><span>In large part, hackers éticos don’t so much “hack” stolen accounts as expertly navigate Instagram’s complicated recovery process.</span></li></ul></div>
			</div>

				<div class="post-container">
			<div class="reading-header"></div>
						<div class="post-content">
				<!-- Article Start -->
				
<p>The moment Anderson Baltar clicked on a link he received via direct message on Instagram, he knew he’d made a big mistake. Suddenly, the 48-year-old radio host from Rio de Janeiro found himself locked out of his account. The person who had hacked it started posting on his behalf, trying to scam Baltar’s followers. The hacker then sent Baltar a WhatsApp message demanding a ransom of roughly 5,000 reais (about $1,006).</p>



<p>“I tried everything I could with Meta [Instagram’s parent company],” Baltar told <em>Rest of World</em>. “But I didn&#8217;t receive any response.” He refused to pay the hacker, and ended up contacting Italo Botelho, CEO of Digital Solutions, a company specialized in “protecting and recovering digital access.” Botelho, who claims to have recovered over <a href="https://www.instagram.com/italofbotelho/">20,000 hacked accounts</a>, charged Baltar 200 reais ($40) and got his account back in about 15 days.</p>



<p>Over the past two years, the popularity of <em>hackers do bem </em>(good hackers) or <em>hackers éticos</em> (ethical hackers) who help recover stolen accounts on Instagram has grown across Brazil, as prosecutor <a href="https://www.mpmg.mp.br/portal/menu/comunicacao/noticias/mpmg-alerta-invasao-de-perfis-no-instagram-e-um-dos-crimes-ciberneticos-de-maior-incidencia-neste-inicio-de-2022.shtml">reports of scams</a> via hacked accounts have simultaneously increased. Though the term “good hacker” was coined by victims, these self-described recovery professionals don’t actually do much hacking at all. Instead, their service appears to be an expertise in navigating customer support: Victims described Instagram’s recovery guidelines as vague, impersonal, and difficult to follow, so they pay hackers éticos to optimize the filing and follow-up of their reports.</p>



<p>“Most hacked account victims don’t get past the first page [of Instagram’s recovery report section] because they don’t actually know what happened and are confused by the options,” Rubsmar Leocadio, who shares tips on account recovery on YouTube, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H-WOoFcyIpg">said in one of his videos.</a> All of the hackers éticos interviewed by <em>Rest of World</em>, while vague about their exact methods, shared Leocadio’s view: Their work is in high demand because users find Instagram’s guidelines on recovering hacked accounts too complicated to navigate on their own. </p>



<p>“I don’t use any apps to invade or hack an account,” Giovanna Napolitano, a 23-year-old from Rio de Janeiro who advertises herself as a hacker ética, told <em>Rest of World</em>. “I just try to understand the situation and orient how the person can get the access back.”</p>



<p>Hacked social media accounts are a worldwide phenomenon. Users generally have unsafe passwords and are too trusting online, Lázaro Bustio Martínez, a cybersecurity researcher at the Iberoamericana University in Mexico City, told <em>Rest of World.</em></p>



<p>The problem is particularly widespread in Brazil. According to the Public Ministry of Minas Gerais, the second most-populous state in the country, Instagram account hacks were among the <a href="https://www.mpmg.mp.br/portal/menu/comunicacao/noticias/mpmg-alerta-invasao-de-perfis-no-instagram-e-um-dos-crimes-ciberneticos-de-maior-incidencia-neste-inicio-de-2022.shtml">most common online crimes</a> during early 2022. Data from Reclameaqui, the country’s most popular site for customer complaint intermediation, shows that about <a href="https://www.reclameaqui.com.br/empresa/instagram/#problem-types">11%</a> of the over 290,000 complaints made about Instagram in the past three years involved hacked accounts. </p>



<p>Dilson Souza, a hacker ético from São Paulo, told <em>Rest of World</em> he’s helped recover over 10,000 accounts in the past year. Although he runs a team of six people, Souza said he needs to hire more because business is booming. He’s amassed over 67,000 followers on Instagram and charges anywhere from 200 to 5,000 reais (between $40 and $1,040), depending on the case. The price varies based on the number of followers an account had prior to the hacking. Victims also need to pay more if they were hacked with a more sophisticated technique — like one that uses an SMS code — as opposed to simpler phishing scams, since this affects the complexity of Instagram’s account recovery process.</p>



<blockquote class="blockquote blockquote--stat">
<p><strong>11%</strong> The percentage of complaints made about Instagram that involve hacked accounts over the last three years in Brazil.</p>
<cite><a href="https://www.reclameaqui.com.br/empresa/instagram/#problem-types">Reclameaqui</a></cite></blockquote>



<p>Instagram’s <a href="https://www.instagram.com/hacked/">guidelines on account recovery</a> suggest users report the hacking directly on the platform. A Meta spokesperson told <em>Rest of World</em> the account recovery process can only be carried out through the platform’s help option, and that there is no external service authorized by Instagram. “By filling out a form, users can send a support request to Instagram so we can quickly help recover access,” the representative said<em>.</em> However, users said Instagram’s guidelines were too vague and ineffective, resulting in frustrating hurdles early on in the report-filing process. </p>



<p>Hackers éticos help victims avoid simple but common mistakes that jeopardize their account recovery process. One of them is deleting the app after being hacked. It&#8217;s something a victim can do out of desperation, said Souza, but doing so breaks the link between a victim’s phone and their account, taking it off Instagram’s records. This makes it harder to validate the victim’s identity, so hackers éticos, first and foremost, insist that users keep the app.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Hackers éticos then help fill out the form, since victims often make basic mistakes when doing so on their own. A common one is not selecting the correct help option from a list of six. For instance, if a person can’t log in because the hacker has changed their username, they might think to select the option “My account got hacked.” While this is technically correct, hackers éticos advise against it: Instagram will disable the account, some said, extending the recovery process. Instead, they say the correct answer is actually “I forgot my password,” giving the users a better chance at recovering their account — either through a two-step verification process or by generating a password reset link to the email address connected to the account. </p>



<p>Victims who have had their Instagram handles changed by hackers also often make the mistake of inputting the original username while submitting an account recovery request. But that username no longer exists, and Instagram sees the request coming from a seemingly nonexistent account. To solve this, hackers éticos recommend the victim reach out to someone they’ve chatted with on Instagram and ask them to go to their old conversation to see what the new username is. That is the one that should be reported.</p>



<figure class="pullquote pullquote--right-rail"><blockquote><p>“You can’t speak to employees, so when you find someone who can help you, it’s easier.”</p></blockquote></figure>



<p>Hackers éticos also share tips and best practices on how to correctly upload an ID verification video. This is a particularly troublesome part of the reporting process, with users often standing in poor lighting or angling the camera incorrectly, preventing their face from being properly identified and failing the ID validation process. Hackers éticos will point victims to something as simple as a white background with good lighting to maximize their chances of success.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Napolitano said these services are also popular because Instagram gives users little information about what happens after filling out the form: how long a waiting period to expect or what to do if technical issues arise during the recovery process. “Meta’s support team is not accessible. You can’t speak to employees, so when you find someone who can help you, it’s easier,” she said.</p>



<p>Users and hackers éticos repeatedly claimed that some hackers éticos also have extra-official contacts among Meta staff, allowing them to help speed up the recovery process. Bustio Martínez said Meta employees working with hackers éticos is very unlikely because the company’s internal safety mechanisms are highly efficient. Meta told <em>Rest of World </em>one of their main safety recommendations is to distrust anyone who says they’re part of Instagram’s security team or offers account verification services, as they’re more likely to steal valuable information from the victim. Though <em>Rest of World </em>was unable to corroborate if hackers éticos indeed have contacts among Meta employees, some still used these claims to charge a premium — around 7,000 reais (about $1,455), Napolitano said.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>



<p>Hacked Instagram users have another recourse that does not require them to resort to paying a stranger claiming to be a “good hacker”: <a href="https://www.dentons.com/en/insights/articles/2022/june/13/a-brief-overview-of-regulation-from-a-consumer-protection-perspective">Brazilian consumer protection law</a>. Procon, the agency in charge of consumer defense and protection, forces consumer-facing companies to provide an answer to a customer’s complaint in no more than 10 days after filing a report. The company in question can face legal consequences and fines if it fails to comply, but only if the user files a complaint with Procon.</p>



<p>That’s how Rafaella Torneri, a 26-year-old from São Paulo, got her account back. When the account was hacked earlier this year, she considered paying a hacker ético, but then deemed it too expensive and tried to do it herself. She first filed a report on Instagram, but it didn’t work. She then filed a report with Procon, which compelled Meta to take action on her case. Torneri got her account back in two days and paid nothing to recover it.</p>



<p>Few people in the country, however, use Procon’s process. <a href="https://idec.org.br/pdf/idec_pesquisa-consumidor-2021.pdf">A 2021 survey</a> by the Brazilian Institute of Consumer Defense showed that although 94% of surveyed users said they had some knowledge of their consumer rights, only 67% managed to solve their problem by filing a complaint. Of them, 30% said they’d actually file a complaint through Procon or a similar entity.</p>



<p>“As long as there’s people willing to pay for a lost password or access, there will be an industry of people recovering them,” said Bustio Martínez. And it’s a booming one: Chrystian Sergio Martins, a hacker ético from Ipatinga, a city in Minas Gerais, claims he has recovered over 5,000 accounts. He told <em>Rest of World</em> he raked in over 780,000 reais (about $150,000) in eight months.</p>
				<!-- Article End -->
							</div><!-- .post-content -->
		</div><!-- .post-container -->

				<footer class="post-footer">
			  <div class='post-footer__authors'><div class="post-footer__authors__author"><a class="post-footer__authors__author-name author url fn clear" href="https://restofworld.org/author/daniela-dib/" title="Articles by Daniela Dib" rel="author">Daniela Dib</a> is a Rest of World reporter based in Mexico City.</div><div class="post-footer__authors__author"><a class="post-footer__authors__author-name author url fn clear" href="https://restofworld.org/author/marilia-marasciulo/" title="Articles by Marília Marasciulo" rel="author">Marília Marasciulo</a> is a journalist based in Brazil.</div></div> 		</footer>

	
</article>

